is-Representation -- tPart Four: The (Mis-)Management of Resources -- tChapter 13. Economics, Politics and the Law in Malaysia: A Case Study of the 1MDB Scandal -- tChapter 14. Collecting, Resisting, and Paying Corporatised Zakat in Contemporary Malaysia -- tChapter 15. Malaysia's Green Movement: Old Continuities and New Possibilities -- tChapter 16. Responsible Resource Management of the Oil and Gas Sector in Malaysia: Issues, Challenges and Opportunities -- tAfterword -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together a group of both international and Malaysian scholars, this book offers an up-to-date and broad analysis of the contemporary state of Malaysian politics and society. Transcending disciplinary boundaries, it offers a look at Malaysian politics not only through the lens of political science but also anthropology, cultural studies, international relations, political economy and legal studies touching on both overlooked topics in Malaysian political life as well as the emerging trends which will shape Malaysia's future. Covering silat martial arts, Malaysia's constitutional identity, emergency legislation, the South China Sea dilemma, ISIS discourse, zakat payment, the fallout from the 1MDB scandal and Malaysia's green movement, Illusions of Democracy charts the complex and multi-faceted nature of political life in a semi-authoritarian state, breaking down the illusions which keep it functioning, to uncover the mechanisms which really underlie the paradoxical longevity of Malaysia's political, economic and social system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aPolitical Science. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.